# TypeScript patterns

Recipes. Pair with `design.md` (the principles) and `code-smells.md`
(what each pattern fixes).

## Branded types (value objects)

```ts
declare const brand: unique symbol;
type Brand<T, B> = T & { readonly [brand]: B };

export type UserId    = Brand<string, "UserId">;
export type Email     = Brand<string, "Email">;
export type MoneyUSD  = Brand<number, "MoneyUSD">;

const EMAIL_RE = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;

export function email(s: string): Email {
  if (!EMAIL_RE.test(s)) throw new RangeError(`invalid email: ${s}`);
  return s as Email;
}
```

Constructors validate. Once you hold a `UserId` / `Email` / `MoneyUSD`,
the rest of the code can trust it.

## Result type — errors as values

```ts
export type Result<T, E = Error> =
  | { ok: true;  value: T }
  | { ok: false; error: E };

export const ok    = <T>(value: T): Result<T, never>          => ({ ok: true,  value });
export const err   = <E>(error: E): Result<never, E>          => ({ ok: false, error });

export function map<T, U, E>(r: Result<T, E>, f: (t: T) => U): Result<U, E> {
  return r.ok ? ok(f(r.value)) : r;
}

export function andThen<T, U, E>(r: Result<T, E>, f: (t: T) => Result<U, E>): Result<U, E> {
  return r.ok ? f(r.value) : r;
}
```

Domain functions return `Result<T, DomainError>`. The application layer
maps to HTTP / CLI exit codes. Or use [`neverthrow`](https://github.com/supermacro/neverthrow)
for a fuller toolbox.

## Discriminated unions + exhaustive switch

```ts
type Event =
  | { kind: "OrderPlaced";    orderId: OrderId; at: Date }
  | { kind: "PaymentReceived";orderId: OrderId; amount: MoneyUSD }
  | { kind: "OrderShipped";   orderId: OrderId; at: Date };

function handle(e: Event): void {
  switch (e.kind) {
    case "OrderPlaced":     return placed(e);
    case "PaymentReceived": return paid(e);
    case "OrderShipped":    return shipped(e);
    default: {
      const _: never = e;
      throw new Error(`unhandled event: ${JSON.stringify(_)}`);
    }
  }
}
```

Adding a fourth variant fails to compile at *every* switch on `Event`.

## Strategy via record-of-functions

```ts
type Renderer = (doc: Document) => string;

const renderers: Record<string, Renderer> = {
  pdf:       renderPdf,
  html:      renderHtml,
  plaintext: renderPlaintext,
};

export function render(doc: Document, fmt: string): string {
  const r = renderers[fmt];
  if (!r) throw new Error(`unsupported format: ${fmt}`);
  return r(doc);
}
```

Strictly typed: when `fmt` is a discriminated-union literal, narrow
the record key type to make `renderers[fmt]` non-nullable.

## Policy pattern — kill the boolean flag

```ts
type OrderPolicy = (o: Order) => Order;

const applyVipDiscount: OrderPolicy = (o) => ({ ...o, total: discounted(o.total) });
const expressShipping:  OrderPolicy = (o) => ({ ...o, shipping: "express" });

export function processOrder(o: Order, policies: readonly OrderPolicy[]): Order {
  return policies.reduce((acc, p) => p(acc), o);
}
```

Caller composes:

```ts
processOrder(order, [applyVipDiscount, expressShipping]);
```

No flag combinatorics, no `if/else` cascade, each policy is trivially
unit-testable.

## Context object — kill parameter bloat

```ts
type ReportContext = Readonly<{
  period:   DateRange;
  currency: Currency;
  tenant:   TenantId;
  locale:   string;
  includeDrafts: boolean;
}>;

export function buildReport(ctx: ReportContext): Report { /* … */ }
```

Internal helpers depend only on the fields they read:

```ts
type PeriodProvider = Pick<ReportContext, "period">;
function summarise(p: PeriodProvider): Summary { /* … */ }
```

## Dependency injection via constructor

```ts
export class PlaceOrderUseCase {
  constructor(
    private readonly orders: OrderRepository,
    private readonly clock: Clock,
    private readonly publish: EventPublisher,
  ) {}

  async execute(cmd: PlaceOrderCommand): Promise<OrderId> {
    const order = Order.fromCommand(cmd, this.clock.now());
    await this.orders.save(order);
    await this.publish({ kind: "OrderPlaced", orderId: order.id, at: order.placedAt });
    return order.id;
  }
}
```

`OrderRepository`, `Clock`, `EventPublisher` are *interfaces*
(declared in `domain/`); concrete implementations are wired at the
composition root.

## Builder for complex configuration

```ts
type Defined<T> = T extends undefined ? never : T;

class HttpClientBuilder<Stage extends "init" | "configured" = "init"> {
  private constructor(private readonly cfg: Partial<HttpClientConfig>) {}
  static new(): HttpClientBuilder<"init"> { return new HttpClientBuilder({}); }

  baseUrl(this: HttpClientBuilder, u: URL): HttpClientBuilder<"configured"> {
    return new HttpClientBuilder({ ...this.cfg, baseUrl: u }) as HttpClientBuilder<"configured">;
  }
  timeout(ms: number) { return new HttpClientBuilder({ ...this.cfg, timeoutMs: ms }) as this; }

  // `build` only exists on the "configured" type-state
  build(this: HttpClientBuilder<"configured">): HttpClient {
    return new HttpClient(this.cfg as HttpClientConfig);
  }
}
```

Type-state in TS feels heavier than in Rust but works the same way:
`.build()` is reachable only when required steps have been taken.

## Schema-first boundary validation

```ts
import { z } from "zod";

export const PlaceOrderCommand = z.object({
  customerId: z.string().uuid(),
  items: z.array(z.object({
    sku:      z.string(),
    quantity: z.number().int().positive(),
  })).nonempty(),
});
export type PlaceOrderCommand = z.infer<typeof PlaceOrderCommand>;
```

In the presentation layer, parse with `PlaceOrderCommand.parse(req.body)`.
Past that point the type is trusted.

## Composition root

One function (`app.ts` or `bootstrap.ts`) wires concrete adapters into
generic use cases.

```ts
export async function buildApp(env: Env): Promise<App> {
  const db      = await connectDatabase(env.DATABASE_URL);
  const orders  = new PrismaOrderRepository(db);
  const clock   = systemClock();
  const publish = createSnsPublisher(env.SNS_TOPIC_ARN);

  const placeOrder = new PlaceOrderUseCase(orders, clock, publish);

  return makeApp({ placeOrder });
}
```

No other module reads `process.env` or constructs adapters.

## React-specific (if applicable)

When using React in `presentation/`:

- Hooks over class components.
- Components are pure of state where possible — push state up.
- Co-locate types with components: `Props` interface immediately above
  the component.
- Prefer `useReducer` for complex local state; the reducer is your
  test target.
- Server Components for things that genuinely don't need
  interactivity; Client Components for things that do.
